1
00:00:06,000 --> 00:00:12,074


2
00:02:09,356 --> 00:02:11,527
- Did you bring my band of Indians?
- Indians?

3
00:02:11,628 --> 00:02:15,010
Yes, American Indians,
musicians to play in my café.

4
00:02:15,116 --> 00:02:17,734
- Oh, you mean Indians with feathers?
- Yes, with noses.

5
00:02:17,836 --> 00:02:20,039
- Like on the American five cents?
- Yes, yes.

6
00:02:20,139 --> 00:02:22,561
- Have you got them on board, yes?
- No.

7
00:02:23,723 --> 00:02:25,217
Thank you, <i>monsieur.</i>

8
00:02:29,931 --> 00:02:33,728
Indians? Indians?
Are you the Wabash Indians Band?

9
00:02:33,804 --> 00:02:34,851
Are you Voyda?

10
00:02:34,924 --> 00:02:37,477
I am Alexander Petrovitch
Moskovich Voyda.

11
00:02:38,027 --> 00:02:39,369
Let's pick it up from there.

12
00:02:39,468 --> 00:02:41,540
We're the boys you hired
to play at your café.

13
00:02:41,611 --> 00:02:44,426
- The Wabash Indianians.
- Indianians?

14
00:02:45,451 --> 00:02:47,240
Is this the same as Indians?

15
00:02:49,611 --> 00:02:51,073
Well, yes, in a sense.

16
00:02:51,180 --> 00:02:54,496
You see, we don't wear our feathers
in warm weather, do we, boys?

17
00:02:54,572 --> 00:02:55,946
- No.
- No, never, never.

18
00:02:56,011 --> 00:02:59,077
- Well, when do we start, Mr. Voyda?
- You don't start.

19
00:02:59,211 --> 00:03:01,546
I cable for Indians and I want Indians!

20
00:03:01,707 --> 00:03:05,482
No pale American face
is going to make me a fool of myself.

21
00:03:05,579 --> 00:03:08,579
Did you ever heard of Alexander
Petrovitch Moskovich Voyda?

22
00:03:08,651 --> 00:03:10,756
- Sure.
- Yes, and how, and how.

23
00:03:10,827 --> 00:03:13,697
As a matter of fact, we hear you're one
of the cleverest fellows in Paris.

24
00:03:13,772 --> 00:03:15,844
In Paris and all Europe.
The whole world.

25
00:03:15,948 --> 00:03:18,533
Well, I was coming to that.
I just wanted to prepare you, that's all.

26
00:03:18,603 --> 00:03:20,294
You got a great bet
in these boys, Mr. Voyda.

27
00:03:20,363 --> 00:03:23,712
- They'll be a knockout in your café.
- They shall never see my café.

28
00:03:23,819 --> 00:03:26,886
I ordered Indians, and what do I get?

29
00:03:31,820 --> 00:03:33,194
Wait, Mr. Voyda.

30
00:03:34,892 --> 00:03:36,201
Huck, do the organ number, quick.

31
00:03:36,299 --> 00:03:38,536
Come on, boys, give us the organ number.
Get the gloves out.

32
00:03:38,603 --> 00:03:39,813
- Oh, Mr. Voyda.
- What?

33
00:03:39,883 --> 00:03:41,127
Aren't you going to
give these boys a chance?

34
00:03:41,195 --> 00:03:42,504
No, why should I?

35
00:03:43,243 --> 00:03:45,447
Sorry, Mr. Voyda,
but I'm afraid you've got to listen.

36
00:03:45,547 --> 00:03:47,817
Just submit quietly
and we'll both keep out of jail.

37
00:05:16,300 --> 00:05:19,496
Well, how did you like that, Mr. Voyda?
You see, you almost made a mistake.

38
00:05:19,563 --> 00:05:21,897
I made a mistake? You made a mistake.

39
00:05:21,964 --> 00:05:23,458
You are not Indians!

40
00:05:25,483 --> 00:05:27,818
The cable mentioned a short engagement.

41
00:05:28,619 --> 00:05:30,245
Well, it was a nice trip over.

42
00:05:30,315 --> 00:05:33,414
It'll be a nicer trip going back,
stoking coals.

43
00:05:38,540 --> 00:05:40,645
Come on, boys, the train for Paris.

44
00:05:49,515 --> 00:05:51,686
A grand total of $13.78.

45
00:05:52,491 --> 00:05:53,669
And a button.

46
00:05:55,019 --> 00:05:58,597
Well, boys, at the rate we live,
that'll last us about two months.

47
00:05:59,275 --> 00:06:01,642
Mother told me
there would be days like this.

48
00:06:01,739 --> 00:06:03,975
Say, listen,
they dance in Paris, don't they?

49
00:06:04,043 --> 00:06:05,953
All we have to do
is find out who pays the fiddler.

50
00:06:06,059 --> 00:06:07,717
Does anyone know anyone in Paris?

51
00:06:07,819 --> 00:06:10,208
That top sergeant brother of mine
gave me some addresses.

52
00:06:10,283 --> 00:06:11,330
Quiet.

53
00:06:12,043 --> 00:06:15,687
Wait! I know somebody, a little girl
who used to live next door to me.

54
00:06:15,755 --> 00:06:19,072
Gee, I was crazy about her, too.
She's a sensation in Paris,

55
00:06:19,179 --> 00:06:21,634
she's a star of some show or something.

56
00:06:22,796 --> 00:06:25,130
- She'll help us.
- Well, what's her name?

57
00:06:25,995 --> 00:06:27,369
What was her name?

58
00:06:28,491 --> 00:06:31,175
Gee, I could find her like that
if I could only remember her name.

59
00:06:31,243 --> 00:06:33,031
Anybody else you know
you can't remember?

60
00:06:33,131 --> 00:06:35,368
Yeah, but I can't think who they are.

61
00:06:35,435 --> 00:06:39,591
I know, it's Lizzie, Lizzie...
Elizabeth Gatz.

62
00:06:39,691 --> 00:06:40,869
That's it. Elizabeth Gatz.

63
00:06:40,971 --> 00:06:42,378
What a beautiful name.

64
00:06:42,443 --> 00:06:46,535
Whether you find your Lizzie or not,
I've got an aunt in Paris. Aunt Minnie.

65
00:06:46,635 --> 00:06:48,391
Can Aunt Minnie use a band?

66
00:06:48,715 --> 00:06:50,788
Probably not. She's a dressmaker.

67
00:06:51,115 --> 00:06:54,595
Well, I've knitted and tatted
all my life, but I've never sewed.

68
00:06:54,699 --> 00:06:57,382
- She's very rich and famous. She might...
- Why didn't you say so before?

69
00:06:57,707 --> 00:06:58,722
She's Roberta.

70
00:06:58,795 --> 00:06:59,875
Roberta?

71
00:07:01,195 --> 00:07:02,854
- This Roberta?
- Yeah.

72
00:07:02,923 --> 00:07:05,192
They tell me in Paris if you
don't buy your gowns from Roberta,

73
00:07:05,259 --> 00:07:06,721
you're not dressed at all.

74
00:07:06,795 --> 00:07:09,348
I see, nude if you don't, and nude if you do.

75
00:07:21,419 --> 00:07:22,880
Grab my bag, will you?

76
00:07:24,492 --> 00:07:27,787
Listen, ask your aunt Minnie if she knows
where we can find Lizzie Gatz, will you?

77
00:07:27,851 --> 00:07:29,924
- Okay. I won't be long.
- All right.

78
00:07:30,635 --> 00:07:33,799
You fellows pick yourselves
some comfortable easy chairs.

79
00:08:20,491 --> 00:08:21,505
Hey!

80
00:08:25,899 --> 00:08:26,946
Hey!

81
00:08:40,891 --> 00:08:44,721
What am I supposed to do here
besides pray? Or can't you speak English?

82
00:08:48,091 --> 00:08:49,913
Well, the old trap won't go.

83
00:08:50,683 --> 00:08:53,498
Oh, what's the use? Just a dumb foreigner.

84
00:08:54,555 --> 00:08:56,082
Oh, here, here, here.

85
00:08:56,315 --> 00:08:58,770
You mustn't do that. You might be killed.

86
00:08:59,451 --> 00:09:02,233
Oh, you speak English.

87
00:09:02,811 --> 00:09:03,826
Ladislaw.

88
00:09:19,035 --> 00:09:21,424
Oh, don't go away. I want to thank you.

89
00:09:21,531 --> 00:09:23,702
Gee, you saved my life.
I'm ever so much obliged to you.

90
00:09:23,803 --> 00:09:25,428
Oh, it's nothing at all.

91
00:09:25,627 --> 00:09:28,660
Oh, I mean you're welcome, of course.

92
00:09:28,763 --> 00:09:30,738
Do you know
where I can find Madam Roberta?

93
00:09:30,843 --> 00:09:32,599
Yes. Come with me.

94
00:09:37,467 --> 00:09:40,249
I didn't really mean that
about a dumb foreigner.

95
00:09:40,507 --> 00:09:41,718
I forgive you.

96
00:09:41,915 --> 00:09:43,322
Gee, that's swell.

97
00:09:43,643 --> 00:09:45,466
You speak English beautifully.

98
00:09:45,563 --> 00:09:47,800
Long ago I went to school in England.

99
00:09:48,923 --> 00:09:49,938
Did you like it?

100
00:09:50,043 --> 00:09:53,753
Oh, yes, I like the English.
And the Americans, too.

101
00:09:54,683 --> 00:09:56,090
Gee, that's swell.

102
00:09:56,411 --> 00:09:58,648
- I'm an American.
- Gee, that's...

103
00:09:59,643 --> 00:10:01,847
I mean, I thought so.

104
00:10:03,611 --> 00:10:05,301
Will you sit here, please?

105
00:10:06,331 --> 00:10:07,379
Thank you.

106
00:10:27,547 --> 00:10:31,541
But Minnie, you've made a mistake
in the year. You don't look a day over...

107
00:10:32,123 --> 00:10:34,359
- Stephanie!
- How do you do, Lord Henry?

108
00:10:34,426 --> 00:10:35,768
My dear.

109
00:10:36,155 --> 00:10:39,188
I saw your cousin,
Prince Peter, last week in Rome.

110
00:10:39,323 --> 00:10:41,844
He asked after you most solicitously.

111
00:10:41,947 --> 00:10:44,914
I hope you told him I had gone to work
and he should do the same.

112
00:10:44,986 --> 00:10:47,442
When all you titled aristocrats get jobs,

113
00:10:47,514 --> 00:10:50,035
maybe Europe can settle down
to a few years' peace.

114
00:10:50,107 --> 00:10:51,351
What is it, Stephanie?

115
00:10:51,451 --> 00:10:55,029
There's a young gentleman outside
from America, waiting to see you.

116
00:10:55,131 --> 00:10:56,986
Young gentleman from America?

117
00:10:57,403 --> 00:10:58,418
John.

118
00:10:58,651 --> 00:10:59,698
John!

119
00:11:00,027 --> 00:11:01,620
Bring him in, Stephanie. Bring him in!

120
00:11:01,723 --> 00:11:03,959
No, wait. Don't let him come
until I've powdered my nose.

121
00:11:04,027 --> 00:11:07,126
Give me that compact, Henry.
Quick, quick, the compact!

122
00:11:07,515 --> 00:11:08,890
How does he look?

123
00:11:13,019 --> 00:11:14,645
He must look all right.

124
00:11:15,515 --> 00:11:17,751
- Send him in, Stephanie.
- Yes, <i>madame.</i>

125
00:11:23,386 --> 00:11:26,648
- This "John from America", who is he?
- My nephew.

126
00:11:26,843 --> 00:11:30,258
I met him when I was there a few years
ago and took a great fancy to him.

127
00:11:30,362 --> 00:11:31,672
He's quite famous in his way.

128
00:11:31,771 --> 00:11:34,870
"All-American halfback" or
"three quarters back" or something.

129
00:11:34,971 --> 00:11:36,596
- Really?
- Yes, you know, it's queer,

130
00:11:36,667 --> 00:11:38,161
but when you
happen to like your relatives,

131
00:11:38,235 --> 00:11:39,512
you like them better than other people.

132
00:11:39,610 --> 00:11:42,229
- And if you hate them?
- Don't be obvious, Henry.

133
00:11:42,331 --> 00:11:44,470
He was the only one of the whole tribe

134
00:11:44,571 --> 00:11:47,156
who was polite to me
during my entire visit.

135
00:11:47,386 --> 00:11:48,793
I like him, Henry.

136
00:11:48,987 --> 00:11:52,402
He's like a big, affectionate,
blundering Newfoundland dog.

137
00:11:52,891 --> 00:11:54,320
I'd like to see him grow up.

138
00:11:54,395 --> 00:11:57,559
- How big is he now?
- Oh, about 6'2".

139
00:12:01,082 --> 00:12:04,628
John, my dear, I'm so glad to see you.

140
00:12:04,731 --> 00:12:06,836
It's swell to see you, Aunt Minnie.

141
00:12:07,707 --> 00:12:10,968
- Here he is, Henry, here is my...
- Newfoundland dog?

142
00:12:11,675 --> 00:12:13,682
I was telling him about you, John.

143
00:12:13,755 --> 00:12:17,072
This is Lord Henry Delves,
a really grand person.

144
00:12:17,915 --> 00:12:21,777
And this is Stephanie, my able assistant
whom I couldn't do without.

145
00:12:30,363 --> 00:12:33,559
Well, young man, I think your aunt
should be very much complimented.

146
00:12:33,659 --> 00:12:35,448
When I was in Paris at your age,

147
00:12:35,515 --> 00:12:37,904
I didn't spend my time visiting my aunts.

148
00:12:38,395 --> 00:12:40,729
Maybe you didn't
have any aunts like Aunt Minnie.

149
00:12:40,794 --> 00:12:42,169
Very prettily said, John.

150
00:12:42,235 --> 00:12:44,537
There aren't any like your aunt Minnie.

151
00:12:44,603 --> 00:12:47,123
Well, goodbye, young man,
I'm off to catch a train,

152
00:12:47,195 --> 00:12:48,951
but in a fortnight I'll be back.

153
00:12:49,051 --> 00:12:51,768
And then, as I understand is the custom
in your country,

154
00:12:51,835 --> 00:12:54,388
we'll go places and do something.

155
00:12:58,491 --> 00:13:01,654
Goodbye, Minnie,
miss me just a little, won't you?

156
00:13:01,883 --> 00:13:03,639
A very great deal, my dear.

157
00:13:10,523 --> 00:13:11,952
Nice old duck, isn't he?

158
00:13:12,059 --> 00:13:13,815
Oh, he isn't so terribly old.

159
00:13:13,883 --> 00:13:16,850
Oh, I didn't mean in years, Aunt Minnie.
I meant I like him.

160
00:13:16,922 --> 00:13:18,002
Do you?

161
00:13:18,459 --> 00:13:20,433
Then you're a good judge of men.

162
00:13:20,922 --> 00:13:23,989
Now, tell me about this young lady
you wrote me about. What was her name?

163
00:13:24,091 --> 00:13:26,033
Sophie. She's given me the air.

164
00:13:26,139 --> 00:13:27,153
What?

165
00:13:27,259 --> 00:13:28,437
We had a row.

166
00:13:28,763 --> 00:13:32,145
Oh, I thought she'd given you an heir.

167
00:13:32,411 --> 00:13:34,069
She must be very stupid.

168
00:13:34,171 --> 00:13:36,276
Oh, no, she's brilliant, really.

169
00:13:36,378 --> 00:13:39,674
She speaks German and French
and everything.

170
00:13:39,962 --> 00:13:41,391
Here's her picture.

171
00:13:42,490 --> 00:13:44,563
It isn't very good of her, though.

172
00:13:45,499 --> 00:13:46,993
She has her points.

173
00:13:47,835 --> 00:13:51,184
I take it you're smarting
over this air she has given you.

174
00:13:51,611 --> 00:13:53,749
Well, I'm still in love with her.

175
00:13:54,618 --> 00:13:56,309
But she says I'm just a hick.

176
00:13:56,411 --> 00:13:58,069
- A what?
- A farmer.

177
00:13:58,523 --> 00:14:00,148
I've got hay in my hair.

178
00:14:01,019 --> 00:14:02,295
I can't talk on any subject,

179
00:14:02,363 --> 00:14:04,272
- I can't dance, I can't even dress myself.
- Ridiculous.

180
00:14:04,379 --> 00:14:06,288
And I don't know anything
about women's clothes,

181
00:14:06,363 --> 00:14:09,658
and when I have to order dinner
it's always meat, potatoes and pie.

182
00:14:09,722 --> 00:14:13,071
Oh, she says that, does she?
Well, we'll show her she's wrong.

183
00:14:13,179 --> 00:14:15,513
Gosh, John's been in there a long while.

184
00:14:15,611 --> 00:14:17,815
Oh, why didn't we go to a hotel first?

185
00:14:17,883 --> 00:14:19,192
Man, I'm hungry.

186
00:14:19,738 --> 00:14:21,713
Come on, Mac, give him the call.

187
00:14:31,962 --> 00:14:33,206
That's my gang.

188
00:14:33,499 --> 00:14:35,768
- I came over with a band.
- A band of what?

189
00:14:35,835 --> 00:14:38,323
An orchestra.
They're the Wabash Indianians,

190
00:14:38,395 --> 00:14:41,242
hired for a job in Paris
and fired through a misunderstanding.

191
00:14:41,306 --> 00:14:44,655
Now they're looking for an engagement.
They're a swell bunch.

192
00:14:47,643 --> 00:14:49,530
They do that rather prettily.

193
00:14:52,635 --> 00:14:54,806
<i>Madame,</i> Scharwenka wants to see you.

194
00:14:54,875 --> 00:14:56,915
She doesn't like her tissue.
She doesn't like the model,

195
00:14:57,018 --> 00:14:59,190
she doesn't like the fit,
and she doesn't like the price.

196
00:14:59,259 --> 00:15:01,462
Oh, you mean she doesn't like it.

197
00:15:01,531 --> 00:15:03,636
Yes, <i>madame,</i> what will you do about it?

198
00:15:03,738 --> 00:15:05,265
Do about it? Let her go.

199
00:15:05,371 --> 00:15:06,385
She'll come back.

200
00:15:06,491 --> 00:15:09,491
She's the rage here right now,
and she's got the best figure in Europe,

201
00:15:09,563 --> 00:15:12,083
but she has to have it dressed,
at least partly.

202
00:15:12,155 --> 00:15:14,064
I'm afraid
she intends to start her screaming.

203
00:15:14,171 --> 00:15:15,665
If she does, stick a pin in her.

204
00:15:15,770 --> 00:15:17,712
Oh, I'd rather use an ice-pick.

205
00:15:20,891 --> 00:15:22,800
This time I left the door open.

206
00:15:31,130 --> 00:15:32,537
Who is she going to stick a pin into?

207
00:15:32,603 --> 00:15:37,359
Scharwenka, a Polish countess who has
spurned the hollow mockeries of society

208
00:15:37,434 --> 00:15:39,823
and gone in for nightclub entertaining.

209
00:15:42,650 --> 00:15:44,211
You can see she's talented.

210
00:15:44,283 --> 00:15:46,170
Do you allow her to make such a noise?

211
00:15:46,619 --> 00:15:49,434
- lf she enjoys it, why not?
- Well, suppose the police come in?

212
00:15:49,531 --> 00:15:51,418
Good, they can take her away.

213
00:15:52,315 --> 00:15:54,289
But she must be insane
to make such a row.

214
00:15:54,362 --> 00:15:56,467
Stephanie may not be safe with her.

215
00:15:56,634 --> 00:15:59,416
- You feel inclined to stop her?
- Yes, I do.

216
00:15:59,674 --> 00:16:02,227
No, no, no, no, no!

217
00:16:02,298 --> 00:16:03,825
You are not the only couturier in Paris!

218
00:16:03,931 --> 00:16:06,451
I am a good advertising
for the house that dresses me!

219
00:16:06,523 --> 00:16:08,563
I do not know why
I come to Roberta anyway!

220
00:16:08,635 --> 00:16:10,642
You... Will you quit pushing me?

221
00:16:11,515 --> 00:16:13,238
I... I beg your pardon.

222
00:16:21,979 --> 00:16:24,215
You can't behave like that, you know.

223
00:16:26,970 --> 00:16:30,167
You big beautiful American!

224
00:16:37,435 --> 00:16:38,929
You are very strong.

225
00:16:40,602 --> 00:16:43,919
You do not understand.
These Latin races must be shouted at.

226
00:16:45,050 --> 00:16:47,952
I'm not a Latin
and shouting doesn't impress me.

227
00:16:50,843 --> 00:16:51,858
Hey.

228
00:16:53,115 --> 00:16:54,937
I shall never set foot in this place again.

229
00:16:55,002 --> 00:16:56,791
You do not know
how they have treated me.

230
00:16:56,891 --> 00:17:00,633
This horrible old woman here.
The greedy old <i>diable.</i>

231
00:17:00,731 --> 00:17:02,192
Easy, she's my aunt.

232
00:17:03,098 --> 00:17:06,295
Oh, well, I was not blaming it on her.

233
00:17:06,714 --> 00:17:08,307
She is really a genius,

234
00:17:09,339 --> 00:17:12,535
but that little shrew who
runs the business. That Stephanie...

235
00:17:12,603 --> 00:17:14,228
But Stephanie is swell.

236
00:17:14,394 --> 00:17:17,361
What, you are her lover?

237
00:17:17,530 --> 00:17:19,123
I've never seen such a place.

238
00:17:19,194 --> 00:17:22,161
No one thinks of anything
but being somebody's lover.

239
00:17:23,258 --> 00:17:25,430
Well, have you never thought of it?

240
00:17:29,083 --> 00:17:30,293
What happened?

241
00:17:31,578 --> 00:17:34,066
