00:37:16,474 --> 00:37:19,288
Since you've been gone, Stephanie
has made a man of the world of him.

474
00:37:19,354 --> 00:37:20,728
He's positively arresting.

475
00:37:22,425 --> 00:37:23,887
You ought to see him, Lord Henry.

476
00:37:23,993 --> 00:37:26,961
Your tailor has surpassed himself.
He looks wonderful.

477
00:37:27,065 --> 00:37:29,618
But then I think
he has the knack of wearing clothes.

478
00:37:29,689 --> 00:37:31,544
Not every man has, you know.

479
00:37:31,834 --> 00:37:34,289
And he has a positive flair for languages.

480
00:37:34,585 --> 00:37:37,138
The way he's taken hold of French
is amazing.

481
00:37:37,209 --> 00:37:40,886
You should have heard him
tell a taxi driver where to go last night.

482
00:37:42,009 --> 00:37:44,343
And Stephanie and I
have given him a few pointers

483
00:37:44,410 --> 00:37:47,028
it would take most men
a lifetime to acquire.

484
00:37:47,513 --> 00:37:49,455
What a start for a young fellow.

485
00:37:50,137 --> 00:37:51,446
<i>Au revoir,</i> my dear.

486
00:37:51,545 --> 00:37:54,392
You never looked lovelier in your life
than you do this minute.

487
00:37:54,457 --> 00:37:55,701
Until tomorrow.

488
00:37:55,769 --> 00:37:58,290
It's always nice to know
I shall see you tomorrow, Henry.

489
00:37:58,393 --> 00:38:00,815
You've been saying
very pleasant things to me, lately, Minnie.

490
00:38:00,890 --> 00:38:03,857
- Not really ill, I hope?
- No.

491
00:38:04,537 --> 00:38:06,162
- Stephanie.
- Lord Henry.

492
00:38:34,393 --> 00:38:37,142
- Where is John?
- Taking his French lesson.

493
00:38:37,273 --> 00:38:38,898
Haven't you heard them?

494
00:38:39,257 --> 00:38:40,337
No.

495
00:39:10,905 --> 00:39:12,214
<i>La</i> winner!

496
00:39:37,561 --> 00:39:39,121
Come on, boys, come in.

497
00:39:44,185 --> 00:39:45,614
- So long, prof.
- So long, prof.

498
00:39:53,689 --> 00:39:55,118
Can I get you something?

499
00:39:55,225 --> 00:39:56,403
No, thank you.

500
00:39:57,050 --> 00:39:58,773
Not even a drink of water?

501
00:39:59,641 --> 00:40:00,688
No.

502
00:40:02,297 --> 00:40:03,475
Sing, please.

503
00:40:14,137 --> 00:40:17,879
<i>Yesterday</i>

504
00:40:18,329 --> 00:40:22,257
<i>Yesterday</i>

505
00:40:22,585 --> 00:40:26,098
<i>Days I knew as happy sweet</i>

506
00:40:26,169 --> 00:40:30,424
<i>sequestered days</i>

507
00:40:30,937 --> 00:40:34,679
<i>Olden days</i>

508
00:40:34,905 --> 00:40:38,963
<i>Golden days</i>

509
00:40:39,161 --> 00:40:43,252
<i>Days of mad romance</i>

510
00:40:43,321 --> 00:40:47,151
<i>And love joys</i>

511
00:40:47,257 --> 00:40:52,243
<i>were mine to take</i>

512
00:40:53,817 --> 00:40:57,559
<i>Mine to give</i>

513
00:40:58,585 --> 00:41:01,847
<i>Free and gaily flaming life</i>

514
00:41:01,945 --> 00:41:06,353
<i>was mine to live</i>

515
00:41:06,841 --> 00:41:11,380
<i>Sad am I</i>

516
00:41:11,545 --> 00:41:16,182
<i>Glad am I</i>

517
00:41:16,409 --> 00:41:19,311
<i>for today</i>

518
00:41:19,417 --> 00:41:23,475
<i>I'm dreaming of</i>

519
00:41:23,865 --> 00:41:28,021
<i>yesterday</i>

520
00:41:35,897 --> 00:41:39,890
<i>Joys were mine</i>

521
00:41:39,961 --> 00:41:42,133
<i>to take</i>

522
00:41:42,681 --> 00:41:47,154
<i>mine to give</i>

523
00:41:47,769 --> 00:41:51,598
<i>Free and gaily flaming life</i>

524
00:41:51,705 --> 00:41:56,658
<i>was mine to live</i>

525
00:41:57,081 --> 00:42:01,521
<i>Sad am I</i>

526
00:42:01,945 --> 00:42:06,168
<i>Glad am I</i>

527
00:42:06,777 --> 00:42:09,973
<i>for today</i>

528
00:42:10,041 --> 00:42:13,302
<i>I'm dreaming of</i>

529
00:42:15,097 --> 00:42:19,886
<i>yesterday</i>

530
00:42:41,845 --> 00:42:44,627
- Sophie, Sophie.
- What's the matter?

531
00:42:44,693 --> 00:42:46,220
Here's an article about John.

532
00:42:46,293 --> 00:42:47,438
He's turned dressmaker.

533
00:42:48,245 --> 00:42:49,651
Can you bear it?

534
00:42:49,909 --> 00:42:52,692
lmagine John Kent in a smart dress shop?

535
00:42:53,525 --> 00:42:56,208
He wouldn't know a smart dress
from last year's awning.

536
00:42:56,277 --> 00:43:00,238
Well, the first place I'll make a beeline for
in Paris is going to be Roberta's.

537
00:43:11,797 --> 00:43:13,487
It's all right, Fernande.

538
00:43:17,877 --> 00:43:21,193
I was just saying goodbye to
a room in which I've been very happy.

539
00:43:21,269 --> 00:43:24,236
But you are not
leaving Roberta's, <i>mademoiselle.</i>

540
00:43:27,573 --> 00:43:29,231
Goodbye, Fernande.

541
00:44:06,037 --> 00:44:07,084
<i>Bonjour, Monsieur</i> Fullback.

542
00:44:07,157 --> 00:44:08,302
I wish to place an order.

543
00:44:08,405 --> 00:44:10,958
Would you mind hemstitching
two dozen touchdowns for me?

544
00:44:11,029 --> 00:44:12,076
Oh, lay off.

545
00:44:12,149 --> 00:44:14,702
Would run up for me two field goals
and a bias,

546
00:44:14,805 --> 00:44:16,593
with the score tied in the back?

547
00:44:16,693 --> 00:44:18,155
Kind of a halfback.

548
00:44:19,125 --> 00:44:22,802
I don't get sore often, but I will in a minute
if you two don't shut up.

549
00:44:22,869 --> 00:44:26,797
Do you plan
fitting the ladies yourself, John?

550
00:44:27,189 --> 00:44:30,353
What a picture. Tape measure around
the neck and pin-cushion on the hip.

551
00:44:30,453 --> 00:44:31,598
I ought to spank the two of you.

552
00:44:31,669 --> 00:44:33,491
Now, don't lose
your sense of humor, Johnny.

553
00:44:33,557 --> 00:44:36,142
Why don't you let a guy alone
when he's trying to figure things out?

554
00:44:36,245 --> 00:44:38,033
She just wants to know
what you're going to do.

555
00:44:38,133 --> 00:44:39,955
- That's all.
- I'm going home.

556
00:44:40,212 --> 00:44:43,474
- But you can't. You're Mr. Roberta.
- I'm not. Stephanie is.

557
00:44:43,573 --> 00:44:46,769
I mean, well, Aunt Minnie left no will,
so her property comes to me.

558
00:44:46,837 --> 00:44:49,586
But she always said
the shop was to be Stephanie's.

559
00:44:49,685 --> 00:44:51,408
- Stephanie's going...
- Yes.

560
00:44:56,309 --> 00:44:57,716
We are astonished.

561
00:44:57,877 --> 00:44:59,284
Well, I'm not astonished.

562
00:44:59,349 --> 00:45:01,771
You mean you're going to give
the whole shop to Stephanie?

563
00:45:01,845 --> 00:45:04,943
Yes, right away. That's what Aunt Minnie
wanted and that's what I want.

564
00:45:05,013 --> 00:45:06,737
You're giving it to her without any...

565
00:45:08,757 --> 00:45:09,837
strings?

566
00:45:09,909 --> 00:45:11,600
What do you mean, "strings"?

567
00:45:11,669 --> 00:45:13,524
Oh, she just means

568
00:45:15,253 --> 00:45:16,365
strings.

569
00:45:18,964 --> 00:45:22,096
Well, you make yourselves comfortable.
I've got to find Stephanie.

570
00:45:27,925 --> 00:45:29,550
I was looking for you.

571
00:45:30,005 --> 00:45:31,728
- Well, hello.
- No, no, no.

572
00:45:32,693 --> 00:45:35,508
Can you tell me why no will can be found?

573
00:45:35,605 --> 00:45:38,474
- Well, because there isn't any.
- Why haven't you been able to find it?

574
00:45:38,549 --> 00:45:41,167
- It must have been destroyed.
- So you admit it?

575
00:45:41,397 --> 00:45:42,510
Admit what?

576
00:45:43,029 --> 00:45:45,712
For years Stephanie has worked
to build this business.

577
00:45:45,813 --> 00:45:47,885
It was hers as much as Roberta's.

578
00:45:48,085 --> 00:45:50,190
<i>Madame</i> could not destroy that will.

579
00:45:50,453 --> 00:45:53,355
- Are you trying to say I did?
- I will not say yes or not.

580
00:45:53,428 --> 00:45:56,112
But it looks queer, very queer.

581
00:45:56,308 --> 00:45:58,348
You... Why, you Russian prince!

582
00:45:58,997 --> 00:46:00,884
I'm still boss of this outfit,
and you're fired!

583
00:46:00,949 --> 00:46:03,731
No, no, I am not fired. I am perfectly cool.

584
00:46:03,797 --> 00:46:05,422
I mean you're dismissed.

585
00:46:06,197 --> 00:46:08,139
You think you can get rid of me so easy!

586
00:46:08,245 --> 00:46:10,514
- Get out!
- You think no one will protect Stephanie.

587
00:46:10,612 --> 00:46:13,231
- Stephanie doesn't need your protection.
- While Stephanie stays here

588
00:46:13,332 --> 00:46:15,242
and remains here, I will protect her.

589
00:46:17,045 --> 00:46:20,787
Aren't you ashamed to be quarreling
like two silly little boys?

590
00:46:21,685 --> 00:46:24,106
Please go, Lad, I'll meet you downstairs.

591
00:46:29,493 --> 00:46:31,119
The Russian nobility burns me up anyway.

592
00:46:31,189 --> 00:46:33,393
They're always sticking their noses
in other people's business.

593
00:46:33,492 --> 00:46:35,347
- You don't like the Russian nobility?
- No.

594
00:46:35,445 --> 00:46:36,852
I don't like his hanging around you.

595
00:46:36,917 --> 00:46:38,543
I was going to give you the shop anyway.

596
00:46:38,644 --> 00:46:42,125
Oh, you are very magnanimous,
giving me something I don't want.

597
00:46:42,325 --> 00:46:43,951
- You don't want it?
- No.

598
00:46:44,437 --> 00:46:45,866
And who are you to give me gifts?

599
00:46:45,972 --> 00:46:48,940
- Wait a minute, you mustn't act like this.
- I'll act the way I choose.

600
00:46:49,045 --> 00:46:50,768
It's your shop, you run it.

601
00:46:50,837 --> 00:46:51,916
Goodbye.

602
00:46:51,988 --> 00:46:53,898
Hey, wait a minute, Stephanie.

603
00:46:54,069 --> 00:46:56,457
I'm sorry, but I can't be a dressmaker.

604
00:46:56,565 --> 00:46:58,834
I couldn't half carry on the business.

605
00:47:00,789 --> 00:47:03,723
- Maybe you could carry it on half.
- How do you mean?

606
00:47:04,757 --> 00:47:06,513
Well, I mean

607
00:47:07,956 --> 00:47:10,225
- maybe we could be partners.
- No, no.

608
00:47:10,324 --> 00:47:11,917
You like it, you take it, Stephanie.

609
00:47:11,989 --> 00:47:13,516
I've got a football team to coach.

610
00:47:13,589 --> 00:47:16,753
No, I wouldn't accept anything
except in partnership.

611
00:47:16,852 --> 00:47:18,347
Not on your life. That's out.

612
00:47:18,453 --> 00:47:21,420
- All right, then I'm out.
- Oh, wait a minute.

613
00:47:22,485 --> 00:47:24,940
<i>Pardon, mademoiselle,</i>
may I finish this now?

614
00:47:25,045 --> 00:47:26,354
Oh, yes, yes.

615
00:47:27,604 --> 00:47:29,011
Oh, wait a minute.

616
00:47:30,229 --> 00:47:31,309
May she?

617
00:47:32,052 --> 00:47:35,086
I mean, yes. Certainly, my good woman.

618
00:47:38,676 --> 00:47:40,684
You'll make a very nice partner.

619
00:47:41,204 --> 00:47:44,783
It isn't generally known that <i>Madame</i>
has been letting me do all the designing.

620
00:47:44,884 --> 00:47:47,634
So we'll have to startle them
with daring styles.

621
00:47:48,149 --> 00:47:50,385
- Partners.
- Partners.

622
00:47:52,597 --> 00:47:54,702
Oh, John, look. We've had a brainstorm.

623
00:47:54,805 --> 00:47:58,350
Instead of you going home, why don't
you and Stephanie become partners?

624
00:48:03,349 --> 00:48:05,039
Huck, you're brilliant.

625
00:48:05,204 --> 00:48:06,960
What do you say, Stephanie?

626
00:48:08,149 --> 00:48:10,996
No, not on your life. That's out.

627
00:48:11,668 --> 00:48:13,556
You'll make a very nice partner.

628
00:48:13,653 --> 00:48:17,646
It isn't generally known that <i>Madame</i>
has been letting me do the designing.

629
00:48:19,477 --> 00:48:22,194
We'll have to startle them
with daring styles.

630
00:48:24,244 --> 00:48:26,000
- Partners.
- Partners.

631
00:48:27,253 --> 00:48:30,002
Countess, you shall be our first customer.

632
00:48:37,588 --> 00:48:38,766
Yvonne.

633
00:48:40,309 --> 00:48:43,276
This we call <i>le Petit Trianon.</i>

634
00:48:43,956 --> 00:48:45,745
If you don't like any of these,
say so, won't you?

635
00:48:45,845 --> 00:48:47,601
Gee, I think they're swell.

636
00:48:51,124 --> 00:48:53,874
And this is <i>le train bleu.</i>

637
00:48:55,669 --> 00:48:58,386
Oh, that one's a honey.
That's the one I'd take.

638
00:49:00,469 --> 00:49:03,731
Do your ecstasies
refer to the gown or the girl?

639
00:49:04,789 --> 00:49:07,342
Oh, I hadn't noticed the girl,
but now that you mention her,

640
00:49:07,444 --> 00:49:08,851
- I'd take...
- Yes?

641
00:49:08,916 --> 00:49:11,251
The gown. Less upkeep.

642
00:49:13,685 --> 00:49:16,532
This is called <i>la sirene noire.</i>

643
00:49:23,285 --> 00:49:25,423
Does not she look wonderful in that?

644
00:49:26,004 --> 00:49:27,411
Marvelous.

645
00:49:27,893 --> 00:49:29,486
Just like a peeled eel.

646
00:49:36,148 --> 00:49:37,709
I don't like that one.

647
00:49:38,549 --> 00:49:39,629
Liane...

648
00:49:41,077 --> 00:49:42,189
Albert.

649
00:49:42,709 --> 00:49:44,945
Maybe we could do something about it.

650
00:49:46,933 --> 00:49:49,835
Albert, do you suppose
we could raise this back a little?

651
00:49:49,908 --> 00:49:52,429
If you don't mind, I'd like that dress out.

652
00:49:53,236 --> 00:49:55,091
- As bad as that, huh?
- Worse.

653
00:49:56,149 --> 00:49:57,840
All right, then it's out.

654
00:49:58,036 --> 00:49:59,563
Take it away, Albert.

655
00:50:01,397 --> 00:50:03,885
This is <i>le ciel gris.</i>

656
00:50:19,925 --> 00:50:21,899
That is the one I will take.

657
00:50:22,677 --> 00:50:26,060
And tall, handsome gentlemen
with large bank accounts

658
00:50:26,164 --> 00:50:28,586
will be asking for my telephone number.

659
00:50:30,324 --> 00:50:31,666
And getting it.

660
00:50:33,204 --> 00:50:35,626
And won't they be surprised
when I answer?

661
00:50:39,476 --> 00:50:42,127
Well, so long.
Tell the Countess I'll be waiting for her.

662
00:50:42,196 --> 00:50:43,276
Where?

663
00:50:43,477 --> 00:50:45,484
Oh, either on the right side
of the Left Bank,

664
00:50:45,557 --> 00:50:47,182
or the left side of the right bank.

665
00:50:48,597 --> 00:50:51,347
- I think you're swell not to be angry.
- Angry?

666
00:50:52,596 --> 00:50:55,793
I hope we're good enough friends
for you to express an opinion.

667
00:50:55,892 --> 00:50:59,188
And I hope we're good enough friends
for you to dine with me tonight.

668
00:50:59,284 --> 00:51:01,227
- Oh, I'm sorry.
- Tomorrow night.

669
00:51:01,908 --> 00:51:03,152
I'm very sorry.

670
00:51:03,957 --> 00:51:06,957
I'll tell you, the night
Huck opens at the Café Russe.

671
00:51:08,693 --> 00:51:09,740
All right.

672
00:51:10,228 --> 00:51:11,788
Gee, that'll be swell.

673
00:51:17,188 --> 00:51:18,236
Yes.

674
00:51:18,309 --> 00:51:20,829
I've always been interested
in newspaper work.

675
00:51:20,932 --> 00:51:22,242
Have you anything more to say?

676
00:51:22,309 --> 00:51:23,683
I think he's said enough.

677
00:51:23,748 --> 00:51:25,090
I haven't any more paper.

678
00:51:25,156 --> 00:51:27,578
Oh, we have reams and reams of it here.

679
00:51:27,813 --> 00:51:28,860
Oh, thanks.

680
00:51:29,668 --> 00:51:32,156
A football player
owning a dress shop is news, isn't it?

681
00:51:32,228 --> 00:51:33,275
Good news.

682
00:51:33,764 --> 00:51:35,520
Well, that's what I say,
almost too good to be true,

683
00:51:35,589 --> 00:51:37,050
and that's why
we want you to have it first.

684
00:51:37,124 --> 00:51:40,702
So that you can write it in your own sweet
charming way that you've made famous,

685
00:51:40,805 --> 00:51:41,982
Miss...

686
00:51:42,948 --> 00:51:46,942
We want you to introduce it
in your own inimitable style, Miss...

687
00:51:47,396 --> 00:51:48,607
- Jones.
- Jones.

688
00:51:48,964 --> 00:51:50,077
Jones.

689
00:51:50,149 --> 00:51:52,866
But I'm still sore about all those
silly jokes they're printing about me.

690
00:51:52,964 --> 00:51:54,371
Yes, but they print it.

691
00:51:54,437 --> 00:51:57,436
Every time they make a joke,
a million francs pour in.

692
00:51:57,829 --> 00:52:00,862
It's a pretty expensive joke
on somebody else, I think.

693
00:52:01,348 --> 00:52:04,316
- Now, when Mr. Kent designs clothes...
- When I what?

694
00:52:04,389 --> 00:52:06,527
Does Mr. Kent design clothes, too?

695
00:52:06,756 --> 00:52:09,145
- No.
- Oh, modesty, modesty.

696
00:52:09,764 --> 00:52:14,237
Mr. Kent's idea is to introduce
the football motif into dress designing.

697
00:52:14,788 --> 00:52:18,137
The outdoor flavor will make
the evening clothes look healthier.

698
00:52:18,245 --> 00:52:21,474
Oh, wait till you see our
end-around-end evening creation.

699
00:52:21,604 --> 00:52:23,492
You know, the one
with the dash-off center.

700
00:52:23,557 --> 00:52:25,313
Has Mr. Kent any more ideas?

701
00:52:25,413 --> 00:52:27,267
- No.
- Oh, yes, thousands and thousands.

702
00:52:27,364 --> 00:52:30,528
As a matter of fact, Mr. Kent's
main idea is to design women's dresses

703
00:52:30,596 --> 00:52:32,003
the way men think they should be.

704
00:52:32,068 --> 00:52:33,727
And how do you men
think they should be?

705
00:52:33,797 --> 00:52:34,844
Not so naked.

706
00:52:34,917 --> 00:52:39,008
Well, well, he means that
if clothes are to clothe, they should clothe.

707
00:52:39,236 --> 00:52:43,033
It's more stimulating
to the imagination, if clothes clothe.

708
00:52:43,588 --> 00:52:45,246
That's very unique.

709
00:52:45,317 --> 00:52:46,364
Yes.

710
00:52:46,437 --> 00:52:50,430
And pockets in all dresses,
especially in the evening ones,

711
00:52:50,725 --> 00:52:52,448
so the women can pack their own junk.

712
00:52:52,516 --> 00:52:54,753
The bulging pockets of the male
will disappear forever.

713
00:52:54,852 --> 00:52:57,089
Women will not have to
depend upon their male escorts.

714
00:52:57,157 --> 00:52:58,466
They'll be much more independent.

715
00:52:58,565 --> 00:53:00,986
As a matter of fact... As a matter of fact,

716
00:53:01,797 --> 00:53:05,058
pockets will make
the female more female.

717
00:53:05,156 --> 00:53:06,236
Very nice.

718
00:53:06,308 --> 00:53:08,730
And gloves attached to the dress,

719
00:53:08,836 --> 00:53:09,916
so they won't get lost.

720
00:53:09,989 --> 00:53:12,672
They'll be worn on a jeweled...
Around the neck.

721
00:53:12,740 --> 00:53:13,820
Brilliant!

722
00:53:20,100 --> 00:53:22,555
Well, I really must be going now.

723
00:53:22,917 --> 00:53:24,291
- Oh, that's too bad.
- That's fine.

724
00:53:27,461 --> 00:53:30,308
- Have you had enough?
- Yes, I think I have quite enough.

725
00:53:30,404 --> 00:53:33,186
- Now tell me, what paper will this be in?
- Paper?

726
00:53:33,316 --> 00:53:35,422
Why, I'm Miss Jones. I'm syndicated.

727
00:53:35,524 --> 00:53:38,110
When you talk to me,
you're telling the world.

728
00:53:40,709 --> 00:53:42,083
How was I, toots?

729
00:53:44,836 --> 00:53:46,495
Pardon, <i>monsieur,</i> a lady to see you.

730
00:53:46,596 --> 00:53:48,931
- Another newspaper woman?
- An American, I think.

731
00:53:48,997 --> 00:53:50,241
A Miss Teale.

732
00:53:50,692 --> 00:53:52,547
Sophie! Send her in, please.

733
00:53:52,804 --> 00:53:54,462
Huck, she's here.

734
00:53:54,628 --> 00:53:57,945
That's great, and just when
you were getting along so swell.

735
00:53:58,724 --> 00:54:00,066
You don't appreciate her.

736
00:54:00,164 --> 00:54:02,269
I know she seems
a little hard and sophisticated.

737
00:54:02,372 --> 00:54:04,161
But underneath she's a pearl.

738
00:54:04,228 --> 00:54:05,722
And a pearl, so I am told,

739
00:54:05,796 --> 00:54:08,000
is the result
of a chronic irritation on an oyster.

740
00:54:08,068 --> 00:54:09,890
What do you know
about anything, anyway?

741
00:54:09,957 --> 00:54:13,186
- I know about everything, every way.
- Then you must know Sophie's swell.

742
00:54:13,284 --> 00:54:17,027
John, every day you act worse,
but today you're acting like tomorrow.

743
00:54:20,228 --> 00:54:21,635
- Hello, John.
- Sophie!

744
00:54:21,733 --> 00:54:23,871
You're awfully hard to see
since you became a couturier.

745
00:54:23,972 --> 00:54:25,914
Not for you, Sophie.
When did you arrive in Paris?

746
00:54:25,988 --> 00:54:27,035
This morning.

747
00:54:27,108 --> 00:54:28,537
How long are you going to stay?

748
00:54:28,644 --> 00:54:30,270
Oh, hello, Huckleberry.

749
00:54:30,469 --> 00:54:31,581
Hello, Soph.

750
00:54:31,844 --> 00:54:33,818
Mother and I
are going to Switzerland on Saturday.

751
00:54:33,924 --> 00:54:36,029
Goodbye, John. I'll see you Sunday.

752
00:54:38,917 --> 00:54:40,826
Don't mind him, he's only clowning.

753
00:54:40,933 --> 00:54:42,078
Thank you, dear.

754
00:54:42,149 --> 00:54:45,662
Well, so you're here now.

755
00:54:45,764 --> 00:54:46,779
Yes.

756
00:54:47,364 --> 00:54:50,877
- Aren't you pleased to see me?
- Sophie, I've tried to forget you.

757
00:54:51,237 --> 00:54:52,666
And have you, John?

758
00:54:54,148 --> 00:54:56,515
I thought I had,

759
00:54:57,092 --> 00:54:58,718
but now I know I haven't.

760
00:55:01,797 --> 00:55:03,203
Gee, you're swell.

761
00:55:04,325 --> 00:55:07,324
John, you have a line
that just sweeps a girl right off her feet.

762
00:55:07,396 --> 00:55:08,858
Yeah, sure.

763
00:55:09,508 --> 00:55:11,232
When are you going to show me Paris?

764
00:55:11,332 --> 00:55:14,049
You'd be bored seeing Paris
with a small-town hick like me,

765
00:55:14,116 --> 00:55:16,156
who only knows how to order
meat and potatoes and pie.

766
00:55:16,228 --> 00:55:18,781
Oh, please forget I ever said those things.

767
00:55:18,948 --> 00:55:21,501
I only said them
because you were going away.

768
00:55:22,372 --> 00:55:23,997
I didn't want you to go.

769
00:55:24,868 --> 00:55:27,650
- I loved you so much.
- It was a funny way to love me.

770
00:55:27,717 --> 00:55:31,743
But, John, darling,
don't you ever say things you don't mean?

771
00:55:31,844 --> 00:55:32,859
No.

772
00:55:39,012 --> 00:55:43,103
Well, maybe I do.
Don't cry, Sophie, I don't like it.

773
00:55:45,605 --> 00:55:48,953
I can't help it. I'm so unhappy.

774
00:55:50,724 --> 00:55:53,277
I came all the way to Paris just to see you.

775
00:55:55,044 --> 00:55:58,306
- Only to find you don't love me anymore.
- But I do, Sophie, honest I do.

776
00:56:00,708 --> 00:56:01,985
Oh, John.

777
00:56:06,852 --> 00:56:10,114
- Oh, I'm sorry.
- Oh, come in, Stephanie.

778
00:56:11,364 --> 00:56:14,430
May I present Miss Sophie Teale?

779
00:56:14,692 --> 00:56:16,514
My partner Stephanie.

780
00:56:17,156 --> 00:56:18,618
How do you do?

781
00:56:19,044 --> 00:56:21,663
When I come in for a new gown,
may I ask for you?

782
00:56:21,764 --> 00:56:23,520
Oh, that'll be swell.

783
00:56:24,613 --> 00:56:26,467
Well, I'll run along.
I know how busy you are.

784
00:56:26,564 --> 00:56:29,913
- No, I'll see you to the door.
- No. No. Business before pleasure.

785
00:56:29,988 --> 00:56:33,021
But I'll save Wednesday for you.
Lunch and dinner and the evening.

786
00:56:33,124 --> 00:56:35,099
That's fine. It's a date.

787
00:56:37,349 --> 00:56:38,843
Goodbye, miss.

788
00:56:51,652 --> 00:56:54,913
- Stephanie, I want to...
- Why, when you have time,

789
00:56:55,012 --> 00:56:59,202
- I wish you'd look over these materials.
- But I want to tell you about Sophie.

790
00:56:59,429 --> 00:57:03,323
- She's very lovely.
- Yes, that is... I mean she...

791
00:57:05,348 --> 00:57:08,479
Holy smokes,
haven't we a date for next Wednesday?

792
00:57:08,548 --> 00:57:11,581
Oh, have we? I'm sure we haven't.

793
00:57:26,012 --> 00:57:28,249
This we call <i>le lys doré.</i>

794
00:57:33,884 --> 00:57:37,113
If I weren't going out with Johnny,
I wouldn't be so particular.

795
00:57:37,212 --> 00:57:40,758
But I'm sure he'll want me to have
something that expresses my personality.

796
00:57:40,860 --> 00:57:43,926
Suppose we have Johnny come in
and help you select something.

797
00:57:43,996 --> 00:57:46,615
He knows so much more
about your personality than I do.

798
00:57:46,684 --> 00:57:49,051
Oh, no. No, please. I want to surprise him.

799
00:57:49,116 --> 00:57:53,010
You know, he's really just a little boy
in spite of his man-of-the-world exterior.

800
00:57:53,084 --> 00:57:56,696
Yes, I suspected that.
I'll see what else I can get for you.

801
00:58:04,060 --> 00:58:05,370
- Oh, hello, Huck.
- Hello.

802
00:58:05,436 --> 00:58:07,803
If you're looking for Johnny,
he's in conference with his lawyer.

803
00:58:07,900 --> 00:58:09,362
Well, then,
maybe you'll have lunch with me.

804
00:58:09,436 --> 00:58:10,930
- Are you busy?
- Very.

805
00:58:11,004 --> 00:58:14,517
I'm trying to find something to suit
the personality of Miss Sophie Teale.

806
00:58:14,620 --> 00:58:16,115
Then you are busy.

807
00:58:16,252 --> 00:58:17,397
Liane.

808
00:58:18,396 --> 00:58:19,890
Excuse me, won't you?

809
00:58:20,476 --> 00:58:22,964
Liane, that dress was discarded.
Why do you have it on?

810
00:58:23,036 --> 00:58:25,108
Albert wanted to make a new top for it.

811
00:58:25,212 --> 00:58:27,481
Oh, all right. Fine.

812
00:58:28,700 --> 00:58:32,890
- Is Miss Teale's personality in there?
- Yes, right in there.

813
00:58:33,372 --> 00:58:35,314
I'll go and torment her a while.

814
00:58:41,724 --> 00:58:44,058
Is that beautiful.
And just made for you, Soph.

815
00:58:44,124 --> 00:58:46,874
- Oh, hello. Do you really think it suits me?
- Oh, certainly.

816
00:58:46,972 --> 00:58:50,070
A little longer sleeves,
it would make an ideal straitjacket.

817
00:58:50,172 --> 00:58:51,285
Some day, by sheer accident,

818
00:58:51,356 --> 00:58:52,851
you're going to say
something funny, Huck.

819
00:58:52,924 --> 00:58:55,258
Oh, Soph, now don't be like that.

820
00:58:55,324 --> 00:58:57,396
Do you mind if I sit here
and help you pick out a gown?

821
00:58:57,500 --> 00:59:00,631
No, I'm trying to find something
that John will like on me.

822
00:59:00,732 --> 00:59:02,325
Something startling.

823
00:59:02,396 --> 00:59:04,949
John loves to be startled by girls' dresses.

824
00:59:05,884 --> 00:59:08,634
Here is a gown
that might please you, Miss Teale.

825
00:59:21,692 --> 00:59:24,594
This gown has both chic
and good breeding.

826
00:59:24,796 --> 00:59:28,953
I'm more interested in its chic.
I can supply the breeding myself.

827
00:59:33,276 --> 00:59:37,106
I know the dress.
Look, Stephanie, you know that one that...

828
00:59:37,404 --> 00:59:41,201
It sort of begins and then in the...

829
00:59:41,340 --> 00:59:42,616
You know, the black one.

830
00:59:42,684 --> 00:59:45,586
- The black one?
- Yes, the one you put aside.

831
00:59:46,396 --> 00:59:47,825
Oh, no. No, I can't.

832
00:59:47,932 --> 00:59:49,721
Oh, yes, you can, Stephanie.
Show it to Miss Teale.

833
00:59:49,820 --> 00:59:51,794
- I know she'd like it.
- Oh, no, Mr. Kent wouldn't...

834
00:59:51,900 --> 00:59:54,966
I'm quite sure Mr. Kent would want
me to see any model you have.

835
00:59:55,036 --> 00:59:57,491
Please have it shown
as quickly as possible.

836
00:59:57,564 --> 01:00:00,760
That's it, Stephanie, please have it shown
as quickly as possible.

837
01:00:00,860 --> 01:00:03,348
Just because it's been set aside
for a marquise,

838
01:00:03,452 --> 01:00:05,973
doesn't mean that it can't be shown.

839
01:00:07,676 --> 01:00:12,149
Very well. Anna, have Liane model
<i>la sirene noire</i> at once, please.

840
01:00:14,076 --> 01:00:17,337
Oh, thank you, Huck.
Now we're getting someplace.

841
01:00:21,116 --> 01:00:23,985
- She'll probably like that dress.
- She's going to like it.

842
01:00:24,092 --> 01:00:25,586
When John sees her in it, oh boy,

843
01:00:25,691 --> 01:00:27,634
he's gonna make her walk home,
ocean and all.

844
01:00:27,740 --> 01:00:30,936
- No, he won't. He's in love with her.
- He only thinks he is.

845
01:00:35,643 --> 01:00:37,749
If he were, would you mind?

846
01:00:39,900 --> 01:00:42,550
I am minding, Huck. Terribly.

847
01:00:46,524 --> 01:00:48,280
Can't you hurry that model?

848
01:00:49,052 --> 01:00:50,874
Yes. Yes, Miss Teale.

849
01:01:00,316 --> 01:01:03,130
Well, now that's the smartest thing
you've shown me. I like it.

850
01:01:03,196 --> 01:01:06,294
It's been discarded.
It wasn't put aside for anyone.

851
01:01:06,363 --> 01:01:09,211
- Huck was mistaken about that.
- Oh, I see.

852
01:01:09,564 --> 01:01:11,985
Well, I think I'll have it just the same.

853
01:01:13,052 --> 01:01:14,361
What shall I do?

854
01:01:14,876 --> 01:01:16,599
You're doing fine.

855
01:01:17,372 --> 01:01:19,477
- How much is it?
- It's only 1,000 francs.

856
01:01:19,580 --> 01:01:21,271
It's hardly worthy of you.

857
01:01:23,484 --> 01:01:26,867
I'm afraid she's right, Sophie.
You know it may not be so becoming.

858
01:01:27,772 --> 01:01:29,976
You're not a very good saleslady.

859
01:01:33,724 --> 01:01:38,513
Maybe I'm wrong, Miss Teale.
That dress might suit you very well.

860
01:01:40,923 --> 01:01:42,963
This is the bit of international diplomacy

861
01:01:43,036 --> 01:01:46,811
I shall boast about to my grandchildren,
the nasty little demons.

862
01:01:48,859 --> 01:01:50,648
I'll take the dress.
But I want to try it on first.

863
01:01:51,772 --> 01:01:53,812
The more I think of it, the more I am sure

864
01:01:53,884 --> 01:01:56,786
the dress will bring out
something elegantly alluring in you.

865
01:01:57,372 --> 01:01:59,347
Well, I always know the moment
I see a dress

866
01:01:59,452 --> 01:02:01,361
whether it'll be right for me or not.

867
01:02:34,300 --> 01:02:35,674
I'll take this drink and then the food.

868
01:02:35,772 --> 01:02:37,397
- Gee, I'm starved.
- Me, too.

869
01:02:37,500 --> 01:02:40,151
- Hello, hello, hello.
- Oh, hello, Huck.

870
01:02:40,443 --> 01:02:42,004
- Hello, Soph.
- Hello.

871
01:02:42,076 --> 01:02:44,148
Oh, say, Huck,
will you take care of Sophie for a minute?

872
01:02:44,220 --> 01:02:46,642
I want to see about a table.
Pardon me, Sophie.

873
01:02:46,715 --> 01:02:49,879
- Here's a drink waiting for you.
- Oh, thanks, John. Thanks.

874
01:02:59,803 --> 01:03:02,520
- Got the new dress on, Soph?
- Certainly.

875
01:03:03,995 --> 01:03:06,963
You don't know it,
but this is a great moment in my life.

876
01:03:07,036 --> 01:03:08,945
- Oh, thank you, Huck.
- Thank you.

877
01:03:09,051 --> 01:03:11,288
Don't you think
this dress does something for me?

878
01:03:11,356 --> 01:03:14,323
- It'll do something for me.
- Oh, now, Huck.

879
01:03:15,132 --> 01:03:19,190
- A dress like this depends on...
- I know, it depends on that shoulder strap.

880
01:03:20,092 --> 01:03:22,645
Has John seen it yet?

881
01:03:26,331 --> 01:03:29,528
- Afraid he won't like it.
- And why not?

882
01:03:30,076 --> 01:03:32,050
He thinks everything I wear is perfect.

883
01:03:32,124 --> 01:03:34,513
If I ever ask him how he likes a dress,
he just looks at me

884
01:03:34,619 --> 01:03:37,686
with calf-eyes and says,
"Gee, darling, you look swell."

885
01:03:38,651 --> 01:03:40,724
I bet he won't say it about that one.

886
01:03:40,796 --> 01:03:43,763
I'll bet you $100 he says,
"Gee, that looks swell."

887
01:03:43,836 --> 01:03:46,487
- Make it francs, and it's a bet.
- Sold.

888
01:03:55,260 --> 01:03:57,878
Look, John,
we want you to settle a little bet.

889
01:03:57,980 --> 01:03:59,835
Sophie has a very important question
to ask you.

890
01:03:59,931 --> 01:04:01,655
Gee, that's swell.

891
01:04:10,300 --> 01:04:13,082
How do you like it? Isn't it a knockout?

892
01:04:13,211 --> 01:04:15,993
It's the worst-looking thing I ever saw.

893
01:04:16,699 --> 01:04:19,001
Gee, darling, you look terrible.

894
01:04:23,804 --> 01:04:25,909
- Who sold it to you?
- Your partner.

895
01:04:26,459 --> 01:04:29,842
She thought it brought out
something elegantly alluring in me.

896
01:04:31,676 --> 01:04:33,498
Oh, she did, did she?

897
01:04:34,300 --> 01:04:37,529
I'm sorry I said anything, Sophie.
It isn't your fault, you send it back.

898
01:04:37,596 --> 01:04:41,490
I will not send it back.
It's the smartest thing in your shop.

899
01:04:41,563 --> 01:04:43,832
But what do you know
about clothes anyway?

900
01:04:43,931 --> 01:04:46,168
You make yourself ridiculous
by even discussing them.

901
01:04:46,236 --> 01:04:49,684
I knew enough about them
to order that thing out of our line.

902
01:04:49,755 --> 01:04:51,282
Let me tell you something, John Kent,

903
01:04:51,356 --> 01:04:53,495
now that you think you know something
about women's clothes...

904
01:04:53,564 --> 01:04:54,774
- Please.
- Now that you are carrying on

905
01:04:54,843 --> 01:04:55,890
- with your dressmaker.
- Shut up.

906
01:04:55,963 --> 01:04:58,003
I won't shut up. You're in love with her.

907
01:04:58,076 --> 01:05:00,051
I could tell it
the minute she came into your office.

908
01:05:00,124 --> 01:05:01,585
Let's go home.

909
01:05:01,819 --> 01:05:04,634
I'll go home and I'll go home alone.

910
01:05:06,716 --> 01:05:08,210
Suit yourself.

911
01:05:09,116 --> 01:05:11,450
- What? You'd let me?
- Why not?

912
01:05:11,835 --> 01:05:15,032
And now we're getting down to cases,
here's something I want to tell you.

913
01:05:15,132 --> 01:05:17,172
You've bawled me out for the last time.

914
01:05:17,243 --> 01:05:18,934
I've stood for all your knocking
and criticism

915
01:05:19,003 --> 01:05:21,687
because it sounded so cute
coming from such a little snip.

916
01:05:21,756 --> 01:05:23,730
And because I thought I loved you.

917
01:05:23,803 --> 01:05:27,665
- Oh, you thought you loved me?
- Yes, and what a sap you've made of me.

918
01:05:28,380 --> 01:05:30,801
Well, it certainly didn't take much effort.

919
01:05:30,875 --> 01:05:33,810
And don't you ever
come crawling back to me again.

920
01:05:34,171 --> 01:05:36,560
Because I'm through. Through!

921
01:05:39,771 --> 01:05:41,266
Do you hear me?

922
01:05:43,451 --> 01:05:44,466
Do you hear me?

923
01:05:44,540 --> 01:05:46,612
Sure, but I thought you said
you were through.

924
01:05:46,683 --> 01:05:48,788
- Well, I am.
- Well, goodbye!

925
01:05:49,692 --> 01:05:50,936
Goodbye!

926
01:05:55,260 --> 01:05:56,438
Noisy.

927
01:05:58,396 --> 01:06:00,916
- Give me a dozen brandies.
- A dozen?

928
01:06:01,083 --> 01:06:02,676
Yeah, and line them up right here.

929
01:07:22,235 --> 01:07:24,472
Is there anything I can do for you?

930
01:07:27,483 --> 01:07:28,530
No.

931
01:07:28,994 --> 01:07:30,139
<i>Think of what you're losing</i>

932
01:07:30,242 --> 01:07:32,762
<i>by constantly refusing to dance with me</i>

933
01:07:32,865 --> 01:07:35,353
<i>You'd be the idol of France with me</i>

934
01:07:35,425 --> 01:07:39,003
<i>And yet you stand there</i>
<i>and shake your foolish head dramatically</i>

935
01:07:39,073 --> 01:07:41,462
<i>While I wait here so ecstatically</i>

936
01:07:41,570 --> 01:07:43,991
<i>You just look and say emphatically</i>

937
01:07:44,065 --> 01:07:48,375
<i>Not this season</i>
<i>There's a reason</i>

938
01:07:48,802 --> 01:07:51,191
<i>I won't dance</i>
<i>Don't ask me</i>

939
01:07:51,266 --> 01:07:53,437
<i>I won't dance</i>
<i>Don't ask me</i>

940
01:07:53,506 --> 01:07:56,473
<i>I won't dance, madam, with you</i>

941
01:07:57,186 --> 01:08:00,928
<i>My heart won't let my feet</i>
<i>do things they should do</i>

942
01:08:02,786 --> 01:08:05,022
<i>You know what? You're lovely</i>

943
01:08:05,122 --> 01:08:07,424
<i>And so what? I'm lovely</i>

944
01:08:07,521 --> 01:08:10,521
<i>But oh, what you do to me</i>

945
01:08:11,009 --> 01:08:14,839
<i>I'm like an ocean wave</i>
<i>that's bumped on the shore</i>

946
01:08:15,586 --> 01:08:19,230
<i>I feel so absolutely stumped on the floor</i>

