where Stephanie was

1048
01:19:50,082 --> 01:19:52,766
I wouldn't be wasting my time
with you, babe.

1049
01:19:53,667 --> 01:19:55,194
I know,
but somebody's got to come and take

1050
01:19:55,298 --> 01:19:57,371
this ridiculous business off my shoulders.

1051
01:19:57,443 --> 01:20:00,705
In the four days I've been here,
my voice is beginning to change.

1052
01:20:01,506 --> 01:20:03,775
John, but wait. Don't hang up.

1053
01:20:06,339 --> 01:20:07,997
He won't come back.

1054
01:20:09,123 --> 01:20:10,879
Now what am I gonna do?

1055
01:20:11,683 --> 01:20:14,944
- You're not asking my opinion, are you?
- Yes. No.

1056
01:20:15,042 --> 01:20:16,733
<i>Pardon, monsieur,</i> but do you think

1057
01:20:16,803 --> 01:20:20,600
we should use <i>matelassé</i> for
the "after twilight" number or <i>paillettes?</i>

1058
01:20:20,706 --> 01:20:22,462
And what about the tippet?

1059
01:20:27,938 --> 01:20:31,321
- Well, what do you think?
- I wouldn't know, <i>monsieur.</i>

1060
01:20:32,643 --> 01:20:35,196
Well, personally,
I go in for the simple things.

1061
01:20:35,299 --> 01:20:38,714
- Which is the simpler?
- There is no difference, <i>monsieur.</i>

1062
01:20:40,387 --> 01:20:43,005
Well, then,
use whichever we have the most of.

1063
01:20:43,107 --> 01:20:44,929
We have plenty of all.

1064
01:20:46,243 --> 01:20:48,315
Oh, we have?

1065
01:20:50,179 --> 01:20:54,335
- Well, then use a little of each.
- A sort of a patchwork quilt.

1066
01:20:54,851 --> 01:20:56,542
Yeah. No.

1067
01:20:58,306 --> 01:21:01,176
It will be newer that way
and have much more chic.

1068
01:21:01,251 --> 01:21:03,771
Tell <i>Madame</i> Blanchard
that's my final decision.

1069
01:21:09,123 --> 01:21:11,643
Stephanie.

1070
01:21:14,787 --> 01:21:18,082
- I knew you'd come back.
- I came back to tell John Kent he's insane.

1071
01:21:18,179 --> 01:21:20,088
Where is he? Look at those.

1072
01:21:24,867 --> 01:21:26,940
How do you think
women are going to react to those?

1073
01:21:27,011 --> 01:21:28,320
Where is Mr. Kent?

1074
01:21:28,418 --> 01:21:31,004
Oh, he's not here.
He's been staying away, too.

1075
01:21:31,107 --> 01:21:35,035
- Who has been running the business?
- Did you say running or ruining?

1076
01:21:35,746 --> 01:21:38,812
Well, someone had to do it.
You and John left it flat.

1077
01:21:39,011 --> 01:21:40,767
But I thought surely he was here.

1078
01:21:40,867 --> 01:21:43,584
Well, if he were, he doesn't know
any more about it than Huck does.

1079
01:21:43,651 --> 01:21:46,618
Not as much.
You are the one who is needed, Stephanie.

1080
01:21:46,691 --> 01:21:47,967
Well, that's impossible.

1081
01:21:48,066 --> 01:21:50,936
Why? Just because you and John
are in love with each other?

1082
01:21:51,011 --> 01:21:54,393
Don't be fantastic, Huck.
John isn't in love with me.

1083
01:21:56,162 --> 01:21:58,846
Is it fantastic when a man
is eating his heart out for you?

1084
01:21:58,947 --> 01:22:01,019
When your name is continually on his lips?

1085
01:22:01,091 --> 01:22:02,880
When he stands around
dark street corners

1086
01:22:02,978 --> 01:22:04,637
just to get a glimpse of you?

1087
01:22:04,738 --> 01:22:06,299
- He doesn't.
- He does, and more.

1088
01:22:06,370 --> 01:22:09,404
Everyone around here knows it
but you, Stephanie.

1089
01:22:09,507 --> 01:22:10,783
And maybe John.

1090
01:22:10,850 --> 01:22:14,047
- But he's always quarreling with me.
- Well, what more can you ask?

1091
01:22:14,146 --> 01:22:17,976
Oh, that's nothing. People in love
are always quarreling with each other.

1092
01:22:18,051 --> 01:22:20,156
Now you take Liz and myself for instance.

1093
01:22:20,258 --> 01:22:22,047
Liz? Who is this Liz?

1094
01:22:22,370 --> 01:22:25,218
Oh, a little country girl from back home
that I'm thinking of marrying.

1095
01:22:25,283 --> 01:22:28,763
You know, big feet, dumb, simple.
Oh, very simple.

1096
01:22:29,667 --> 01:22:33,015
Well, the simple and dumb ones
make the best wives sometimes.

1097
01:22:33,602 --> 01:22:37,050
Well, forgetting about this girl of Huck's
from back home, with the big feet,

1098
01:22:37,122 --> 01:22:39,261
what about Roberta? What about John?

1099
01:22:39,331 --> 01:22:42,527
Yes, Stephanie, you must come back
for Aunt Minnie's sake.

1100
01:22:44,291 --> 01:22:46,560
No, I'm sorry. I can't.

1101
01:22:46,882 --> 01:22:48,638
Stephanie, you must.

1102
01:22:48,867 --> 01:22:50,143
Come in.

1103
01:22:50,659 --> 01:22:52,153
Oh, I'm sorry.

1104
01:22:52,323 --> 01:22:54,876
Oh, <i>mademoiselle,</i> I am so happy.
Now you can...

1105
